Specifically, you could use k-means clustering to identify these clusters in the data.

(K-means is a common unsupervised learning technique.)

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/eiDX40MTct

[20/26]

Let's say you have a dataset.

The dataset has 2 X variables (but the Y variable is absent).

If you plot the data, you (as a human) can see that there is structure in the data.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/6XzbYflDgD

[19/26]

A quintessential example of this is the use of *clustering* algorithms to find groups in a dataset

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning #data

[18/26]

Unsupervised learning typically serves a different function.

We typically use unsupervised learning to find structure in the input data.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning #data https://t.co/yD3CVR9UXK

[17/26]

For a machine learning beginner, this might seem strange:

In unsupervised learning, there's no target Y variable to predict.

Isn't machine learning about predicting things?

No ... not always.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning

[16/26]

In unsupervised learning, there's no structured output to predict.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning

[15/26]

Remember: in unsupervised learning, the data has input X variables ...

But the target Y variable is completely absent.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/61lfrrYvzy

[13/26]

In supervised learning, the target Y variable supervises the learning process.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/DOR0pYcjVy

[12/26]

The Y variable acts as a point of reference so the algorithm can check itself and correct its errors.

The model learns to make predictions, and can then compare its predictions against the actual Y variable.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/M2D9H6MFxk

[11/26]

But why do we call it "supervised" learning?

Because the Y variable *supervises* the learning algorithm when we train the model.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning

[10/26]

When we train a supervised learning model, we use an algorithm that learns how to predict Y on the basis of the X variables.

That's really it!

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning

[9/26]

But in supervised learning, there is also a "Y" variable that we're trying to predict.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning

[8/26]

These input variables are sometimes called the X variables

They are also sometimes called "predictors" or "features"

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/qGRJ1N92qs

[7/26]

When we do supervised learning, the data has both *input* variables and a *target* variable.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/K6znMkLsbo

[5/26]

That being said, it can be helpful to understand the difference between regression and classification as well.

You can read about regression vs. classification here:

https://t.co/CDeTYZOjXF

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning

[3/26]

The essential difference between supervised and unsupervised learning has to do with the *data*

In supervised learning, there is a so-called "target" variable that we're trying to predict.

In UNsupervised learning, there is no target.

#datascience #AI #MachineLearning https://t.co/rdTGcqF22w

If you've started studying machine learning, you've probably heard the terms "supervised" and "unsupervised".

These terms often confuse beginners in ML and data science.

So here, I'll quickly explain.
